<paragraph blockId="28.[264,1323,1828,1894]" lastBlockId="29.[264,1325,284,590]" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
These are the well­known “honeypot ants”, whose colonies include a subgroup of specialized workers (repletes) devoted to storage of liquid food in their swollen abdomens. Species of 
<emphasis box="[349,520,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Myrmecocytus</emphasis>
are restricted to the western 
<collectingCountry box="[861,1018,284,310]" name="United States of America" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">United States</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1183,1272,284,310]" name="Mexico" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and are found primarily in desert habitats. Snelling’s (
<number box="[871,932,324,350]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1976.0">1976</number>
) landmark revision of the genus also contains much useful biological information.
</paragraph>
